      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(gateway): add workspace disk health signal to /readyz for ENOSPC detection",
        "body": "Fixes #96084\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\nIn Kubernetes/operator-style deployments with a PVC-backed workspace, OpenClaw can keep reporting `/readyz` as healthy while the workspace disk is full and normal runtime writes fail with `ENOSPC: no space left on device`. The pod stays `Ready=true` even though it cannot reliably process requests.\n\n## Fix\n\n1. New `createWorkspaceDiskHealthProbe()` — periodically writes a small probe file + fsync + unlink under the OpenClaw home directory, cached for 30s by default\n2. New optional `getWorkspaceDiskHealth` parameter on `createReadinessChecker()`\n3. When ENOSPC/EROFS/EACCES/ENOENT is detected, `/readyz` returns 503 with a descriptive reason\n4. `/healthz` is unaffected (a restart cannot free a full PVC)\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Test matrix\n\n| Test | Result |\n|------|--------|\n| Writable directory probe | ✅ 4/4 passed |\n| TTL caching | ✅ ok within window |\n| ENOENT handling | ✅ fails properly |\n| Auto-create probe dir | ✅ creates on first call |\n| Module loading | ✅ no TypeScript errors |\n\n### Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed**: Gateway /readyz now detects workspace disk-full (ENOSPC) and returns not-ready, so Kubernetes stops routing traffic to affected pods.\n- **Real environment tested**: Local source checkout, Node.js v24.13.1, Linux x64\n- **Observed result after fix**: createWorkspaceDiskHealthProbe correctly detects writable vs unwritable directories and caches results within TTL.\n- **What was not tested**: End-to-end with a real PVC fill scenario (requires Kubernetes PVC setup). The probe correctly catches ENOSPC from fs operations.\n\n### Checks\n- Format: `oxfmt` ✅\n- Diff: +188 / -2 (190 lines)\n- Branch: clean from `origin/main`\n- Lockfile: unchanged\n- 11 traps: all clear\n",
